## Predicted/Estimated probability

-   [Predicted *probability*]{style="color:#4472C4"} is **NOT** our [predicted *outcome*]{style="color:#D6295E"}

    -   We **cannot interpret** it as the predicted $Y$ for individuals with certain covariate values

    -   Example: our [predicted probability]{style="color:#4472C4"} does not tell us if one individual will or will not be diagnosed with late stage breast cancer

 

-   The [predicted probability]{style="color:#4472C4"} is the estimate of the **mean** (i.e., proportion) of individuals at a certain age who are diagnosed with late stage breast cancer

-   We can use the [predicted/estimated probability]{style="color:#4472C4"} to **predict** the [outcome]{style="color:#D6295E"}

## Predicted outcome

-   Typically, the [predicted probability]{style="color:#4472C4"} is the **most important thing to use in a clinical setting**

 

-   If you ever need to **predict the outcome itself** (from logistic regression with binary outcome):

    -   Remember that the [predicted probability]{style="color:#4472C4"} can be used in a Bernoulli (or Binomial with $n=1$) distribution to find the [predicted *outcome*]{style="color:#D6295E"}

-   If outcome is something like counts, then we would use a Poisson distribution

 

-   By putting it back through a Bernoulli/binomial distribution, we are **re-introducing the random component of our observed outcome**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
set.seed(8392)
rbinom(n=1, size=1, prob = pred$fit)
